{{Infobox University | name = Advanced Research Centre for Bamboo and Rattan (ARCBR) | native_name = | image_name = | image_size = | caption = | established = 2004 | type = [[Education]] and [[Research institute]] | free_label = Acronym | free = ARCBR | city = [[Aizawl]] | state = [[Mizoram]] | country = [[India]] | coor = | campus = [[Urban area|Urban]] | parent = [[Indian Council of Forestry Research and Education|ICFRE]] | website = {{URL|1=http://icfre.org/index.php?linkid=sublnk450352&link=1|2=icfre.org}} }}
'''Advanced Research Centre for Bamboo and Rattan (ARCBR)'''<ref>http://icfre.org/index.php?linkid=sublnk450352&link=1</ref><ref>http://www.icfre.gov.in/UserFiles/File/Institute-RFRI-2011/2012/Report-ARCBR-26Mar12.pdf</ref> Aizawl was established in 2004 as an advanced research centre under the [[Indian Council of Forestry Research and Education]], [[Dehradun]].
==See also== * [[Indian Council of Forestry Research and Education]] * [[Van Vigyan Kendra|Van Vigyan Kendra (VVK)]] Forest Science Centres
==References== {{Reflist}}
[[Category:Bamboo]] [[Category:Calamoideae]] [[Category:Organisations based in Mizoram]] [[Category:Indian forest research institutes]] [[Category:Forestry education in India]] [[Category:Government agencies of India|Forestry Research and Education]] [[Category:Indian Council of Forestry Research and Education]] [[Category:Ministry of Environment and Forests (India)]] [[Category:Research institutes in Mizoram]]

The '''Emin Valley''' ({{zh|c=额敏谷地|p=Émǐn gǔdì}}) is located on the [[China]]-[[Kazakhstan]] border, in [[Central Asia]]. It has an area of about {{convert|65000|km2|mi2}}. Its main waterway is the [[Emil River]].
Administratively, the Emin Valley occupies areas of [[Tacheng Prefecture]] in the [[Xinjiang]] Region of north-western China; and in [[East Kazakhstan Province]] of eastern Kazakhstan.
==Ecology== The Emin Valley has a [[steppe]] ecosystem of mostly [[grassland]]s; with two [[saline lake]]s, [[Lake Alakol|Alakol]] and [[Lake Sasykkol|Sasykkol]]; and mountains with temperate climates.
The Emin Valley Steppe is a [[Palearctic]] [[ecoregion]] in the [[Temperate grasslands, savannas, and shrublands]] [[Biome]]. It lies within the vast and larger [[Eurasian Steppe]].
==Hydrology== [[Orography|Orographically]], the Emil Valley is an [[endorrheic basin]]. In the north, the [[Tarbagatai Mountains]] separate it from the [[Lake Zaysan]] basin, which is part of the basin of the [[Irtysh]] River, eventually draining into the [[Arctic Ocean]]. In the southeast, another series of mountain ranges separate it from the [[Dzungaria]]n Basin ([[Gurbantünggüt Desert]]).
The Emin Valley's main watercourse is the [[Emil River|Emin (Emil) River]], which flows in the general western direction, receiving numerous streams flowing from the Tarbagatai Mountains and carrying their water to Lake Alakol.
[[Lake Alakol]] and [[Lake Sasykkol]], situated in the western (Kazakhstan) part of the valley, are the homes of the rare [[Dalmatian pelican]] and [[relict gull]].
==See also== *[[Eurasian Steppe]] *[[Temperate grasslands, savannas, and shrublands]]
