{{short description|A tsunami-like wave of meteorological origin}} {| class="wikitable" style="float:right;margin-left:0.5em;" |+Some meteotsunami events |- !Area !! Country !! Wave height<!--peak to trough--> (m) !! Fatalities |- |[[Vela Luka]] (21 June 1978)<ref>{{cite web|last1=National Tsunami Hazard Mitigation Program|title=Meteotsunami Fact Sheet|url=http://nws.weather.gov/nthmp/meteotsunamis.html|website=Weather.Gov|publisher=National Weather Service|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref><ref name="Monserrat"/>{{rp|1046}} |Croatia |5.9 |0 |- |[[Nagasaki, Nagasaki|Nagasaki]] Bay (31 March 1979)<ref name="NOAA Examination"/> |Japan |5 |3 |- |[[Pohang]] Harbour |Korea |0.8 | |- |[[Kent]] and [[Sussex]] coasts (20 July 1929)<ref name="BGS2011">{{cite web|title=Tsunami or meteotsunami?|url=http://www.bgs.ac.uk/research/highlights/2011/tsunamiSWEngland2011.html|website=British Geological Survey|publisher=British Geological Survey|accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref> |UK |3.5-6 |2 |- |[[Longkou]] Harbour (1 September 1980)<ref name="Monserrat"/>{{rp|1044}} |China |3 | |- |[[Ciutadella]] Harbour (15 June 2006)<ref name="NOAA Examination"/> |Spain |4 | |- |Gulf of [[Trieste]] |Italy |1.5 | |- |West [[Sicily]] |Italy |1.5 | |- |[[Malta]] |Malta |1 | |- |[[Chicago]], IL (26 June 1954)<ref name="NOAA Examination"/> |[[United States of America|US]] |3 |7 |- |[[Daytona Beach]], FL (3-4 July 1992)<ref name="NOAA Examination"/><ref name="HuffPost">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/12/12/meteotsunamis_n_2286374.html|title=Freak 'Meteotsunamis' Can Strike On A Sunny Day|author=Becky Oskin|publisher=Huffington Post|date=12 December 2012|accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> |US |3.5 |0 |- |[[Ciutadella]] Habour & [[Alcudia]] |Spain |1,8 |0 |}
A '''meteotsunami''' or '''meteorological tsunami'''<ref>[http://ioc3.unesco.org/itic/files/tsunami_glossary_small.pdf Tsunami Glossary 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716100504/http://ioc3.unesco.org/itic/files/tsunami_glossary_small.pdf |date=16 July 2011 }}, UNESCO</ref> is a [[tsunami]]-like [[wave]] of [[meteorological]] origin. Meteotsunamis are generated when rapid changes in [[barometric pressure]] cause the displacement of a body of water. In contrast to "ordinary" impulse-type tsunami sources, a traveling atmospheric disturbance normally interacts with the ocean over a limited period of time (from several minutes to several hours).<ref name="Monserrat">{{cite journal|last=Monserrat|first=S. |author2=Vilibić I. |author3=Rabinovich A.B|year=2006|title=Meteotsunamis: atmospherically induced destructive ocean waves in the tsunami frequency band|journal=Natural Hazards and Earth System Sciences|volume=6|pages=1035–1051|url=http://hal-sde.archives-ouvertes.fr/docs/00/29/93/94/PDF/nhess-6-1035-2006.pdf|accessdate=23 November 2011|doi=10.5194/nhess-6-1035-2006|issue=6}}</ref> Tsunamis and meteotsunamis are otherwise similar enough that it can be difficult to distinguish one from the other, as in cases where there is a tsunami wave but there are no seismic records of an earthquake.<ref name="Monserrat"/>{{rp|1036}}
Only about 3% of historical tsunami events (from 2000 BC through 2014) are known to have meteorological origins, although their true prevalence may be considerably higher than this because 10% of historical tsunamis have unknown origins, tsunami events in the past are often difficult to validate, and meteotsunamis may have previously been misclassified as [[seiche]] waves.<ref name="NOAA Examination"/>
Meteotsunamis are restricted to local effects because they lack the energy available to significant seismic tsunami. However, when they are amplified by resonance they can be hazardous.<ref name="Monserrat"/> A meteotsunami that struck Nagasaki Bay on 31 March 1979 achieved a maximum wave height of 5 meters; there were three fatalities.<ref name="NOAA Examination">{{cite web|last1=Bailey|first1=Kathleen|last2=DiVeglio|first2=Christopher|last3=Welty|first3=Ashley|title=An Examination of the June 2013 East Coast Meteotsunami Captured By NOAA Observing Systems (NOAA Technical Report NOS CO-OPS 079)|url=http://tidesandcurrents.noaa.gov/publications/NOS_COOPS_079.pdf|website=NOAA.Gov|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> A three-meter wave that hit the Chicago waterfront in 1954 swept people off of piers, drowning seven.<ref name="NOAA Examination"/>{{rp|10}}
In some parts of the world, they are common enough to have local names: ''rissaga'' ([[Catalan language|Catalan]]), ''ressaca''{{cn|date=November 2016}} ([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]), ''milgħuba'' ([[Maltese language|Maltese]]), ''marrobbio'' ([[Italian language|Italian]]), ''abiki'' ([[Japanese language|Japanese]]), ''šćiga'' ([[Croatian language|Croatian]]).<ref name="Monserrat"/> Some bodies of water are more susceptible than others, including anywhere that the natural resonance frequency matches that of the waves, such as in long and narrow bays, particularly where the inlet is aligned with the oncoming wave.<ref name="NOAA Examination"/>{{rp|4}} Examples of particularly susceptible areas include Nagasaki Bay,<ref name="Monserrat"/>{{rp|1038–1040}}<ref name="NOAA Examination"/>{{rp|8}} the eastern [[Adriatic Sea]],<ref name="Monserrat"/>{{rp|1046}}<ref name="NOAA Examination"/>{{rp|8}} and the Western Mediterranean.<ref name="Monserrat"/>{{rp|1044}}
