The [[Bayer designation]] '''Nu Lupi''' (ν Lup / ν Lupi) is shared by two [[star]]s, in the [[constellation]] [[Lupus (constellation)]]: *[[Nu1 Lupi|ν¹ Lupi]] *[[Nu2 Lupi|ν² Lupi]]
{{SIA |astronomical objects}}
[[Category:Bayer objects|Lupi, Nu]] [[Category:Lupus (constellation)]]

'''Robert D. Cess''' is professor emeritus of atmospheric sciences at [[Stony Brook University]]. He earned his bachelor of science degree in mechanical engineering from [[Oregon State University]] and his master's degree from [[Purdue University]] in Indiana in 1956.<ref name=cess-osu/> Cess received a Ph.D. from the [[University of Pittsburgh]] in 1959.<ref name=cess-osu/> He is a recognized leader in the fields of climate change and atmospheric radiation transfer.<ref name=cess-osu>{{cite web |url=http://engr.oregonstate.edu/oregonstater/citation.php?id=40 |title=1998 Engineering Hall of Fame |year=1998 |accessdate=14 March 2009 |author=Oregon State University |work=Oregon Stater Awards |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100603205201/http://engr.oregonstate.edu/oregonstater/citation.php?id=40 |archivedate=3 June 2010 |df= }}</ref> His research interest involve modeling of climate feedbacks that can either amplify or diminish global [[climate change]], and interpreting surface and satellite [[remote sensing]] data.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://atmos.msrc.sunysb.edu/npages/Faculty_Prof/Cess.html |title=Robert D. Cess |date=16 March 2004 |accessdate=14 March 2009 |author=Robert D. Cess |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720052312/http://atmos.msrc.sunysb.edu/npages/Faculty_Prof/Cess.html |archivedate=20 July 2011 |df= }}</ref>

He has been a part of studies which have found problems with the ability of model the transmission of shortwave radiation through a cloud-free atmosphere, and designed an experiment to test the accuracy of the models. They reported that they found agreement between the models and the observations of clear-sky shortwave radiation at the surface for the period studied, 1985 to 1988.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/Features/ClearDay/ |title=On a Clear Day (DAAC Study) |date=12 April 2000 |accessdate=14 March 2009 |publisher=[[NASA]] |work=Earth Observatory |author=Carol Smith }}</ref> Cess was a lead author of the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] and worked with the [[National Science Foundation]] on understanding greenhouse warming and its associated policy implications.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://commcgi.cc.stonybrook.edu/artman/publish/printer_1005.shtml |title=Stony Brook University Professor Robert Cess Honored By American Meteorological Society |date=6 February 2006 |accessdate=14 March 2009 |work=Faculty/Student Awards |author=Stony Brook University }}</ref>

==Awards==
Cess has won numerous awards, including NASA's highest scientific honor&mdash;the NASA Exceptional Scientific Achievement Medal in 1989.<ref name=cess-osu/> In 2006, he received the ''Jule G. Charney Award'', which is awarded to scientists in recognition of significant research in the atmospheric or hydrologic sciences, from the [[American Meteorological Society]] "for his outstanding contributions to our understanding of the science of atmospheric radiation and climate change and the role of clouds in climate models."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ametsoc.org/awards/2006recipients.pdf |title=Awards, Fellows, and Honorary Members 2006 |year=2006 |accessdate=14 March 2009 |author=American Meteorological Society }}</ref>

